        "action": { "type": "default", "associatedEntities": {} },
        "body": "Hey there! :) \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThis is a great question from Good Cuppa about adding custom fields to Locksmith's access control flow. I'm pretty sure this is possible using Locksmith's Liquid keys, but it'll require some custom development work.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eThe general idea would be:\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e1. Create a lock on the restricted page, using a Liquid key\u003cbr\u003e2. In the Liquid key, render an HTML form with fields for email and order number \u003cbr\u003e3. When the form is submitted, use Liquid to:\u003cbr\u003e   - Validate the email and order number against Shopify's orders \u003cbr\u003e   - If valid, set a cookie or query parameter granting access\u003cbr\u003e   - Redirect back to the page, where the Liquid key will now pass\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eIt's a bit involved, but definitely doable for someone comfortable with Liquid and web development. Might be a good idea for one of us to mock up a proof of concept or starter template.\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eWhat do you all think? Anyone want to take a crack at an initial reply to Good Cuppa outlining the approach? I'm happy to collaborate, but I think it would be awesome if someone else gave it a shot! \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e@Erica @Jed @Tristan - any of you want to run with this one? No pressure of course, just putting it out there! I think it could be a fun learning opportunity. :)\u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003eLet me know if any other thoughts or ideas come to mind! This is the kind of creative puzzle that Locksmith really shines at.",
